ith the previous plan.\\n\\n    Wait, I\'ll check if I can use the full 15 words.\\n    Line 1: I told a joke about a joke last week. (9)\\n    Line 2: It had absolutely no punchline, literally. (6)\\n    Total 15 words.\\n    This hits the limit exactly.\\n    I\'ll risk it because it\'s exactly the limit, not over.\\n    \\\"STRICT LIMIT: 15 words total.\\\" usually means <= 15.\\n    But to be absolutely safe against strict counters, I should stay under.\\n    I\'ll drop \\\"last week\\\". 13 words is fine.\\n    Simplicity is key.\\n\\n    Final check:\\n    Line 1: I told a joke about a joke.\\n    Line 2: It had absolutely no punchline, literally.\\n    13 words.\\n    Okay.\",\"reasoning_details\":[{\"type\":\"reasoning.text\",\"text\":\"Thinking Process:\\n\\n1.  **Analyze the Request:**\\n    *   Topic: A joke about a joke.\\n    *   Format: 2-line stand-up joke.\\n    *   Line 1: Setup.\\n    *   Line 2: Punchline.\\n    *   Constraint: STRICT LIMIT 15 words total.\\n    *   Output: ONLY the 2 lines. No explanations, no prefixes, no meta text.\\n\\n2.  **Drafting Ideas:**\\n    *   Idea 1: I told a joke about jokes. It didn\'t land. (9 words) - A bit weak.\\n    *   Idea 2: Why did the joke break up? It had too much punchline. (11 words) - Not really a joke about a joke.\\n    *   Idea 3: My joke about jokes fell flat. It had no laughs. (10 words) - Okay, but maybe too literal.\\n    *   Idea 4: I wrote a joke about a joke. It was dry. (10 words) - Pun on \\\"dry humor\\\"?\\n    *   Idea 5: I told a joke about jokes yesterday. Nobody got it. (11 words) - A bit clich\\u00e9.\\n    *   Idea 6: I brought a joke to the comedy club. It got banned. (11 words) - Funny, but maybe not meta enough.\\n    *   Idea 7: Why did the joke go to therapy? It had commitment issues. (12 words) - Personification, okay.\\n    *   Idea 8: I made a joke about telling jokes. It missed the mark. (11 words) - Too literal.\\n    *   Idea 9: My joke about jokes was so dull, it fell a